Young Global Leaders of the World Economic Forum. 

An overview of some WEF Young Global Leaders (2005-2021) and Global Leaders for Tomorrow (1993-2003) in politics and the media.

United States

Politics and Policy
Jeffrey Zients (White House Coronavirus Response Coordinator since 2021, selected in 2003), Jeremy Howard (co-founder of lobby group ‚Äúmasks for all‚Äù, selected in 2013), California Governor Gavin Newsom (selected in 2005), Peter Buttigieg (selected in 2019, candidate for US President in 2020, US secretary of transportation since 2021), Chelsea Clinton (Clinton Foundation board member), Huma Abedin (Hillary Clinton aide, selected in 2012), Nikki Haley (US ambassador to the UN, 2017-2018), Samantha Power (US ambassador to the UN, 2013-2017, USAID Administrator, since 2021), Ian Bremmer (founder of Eurasia Group), Bill Browder (US-British financier), Jonathan Soros (son of George Soros), Kenneth Roth (director of Human Rights Watch), Paul Krugman (economist, selected in 1995), Lawrence Summers (US Secretary of the Treasury, 1999-2001, selected in 1993), Black Lives Matter co-founder Alicia Garza (selected in 2020).
Media
CNN medical analyst Leana Wen (selected in 2018), CNN chief medical correspondent Sanjay Gupta, Covid Twitter personality Eric Feigl-Ding (a ‚ÄòWEF Global Shaper‚Äò since 2013), Andrew Ross Sorkin (New York Times financial columnist), Thomas Friedman (New York Times columnist, selected in 1995), George Stephanopoulos (ABC News, 1993), Lachlan Murdoch (CEO of Fox Corporation, co-chair of News Corp.).
Technology and Social Media
Microsoft founder Bill Gates (1993), former Microsoft CEO Steven Ballmer (2000-2014, selected in 1995), Amazon founder Jeff Bezos (1998), Google co-founders Sergey Brin and Larry Page (2002/2005), former Google CEO Eric Schmidt (2001-2011, selected in 1997), Wikipedia co-founder Jimmy Wales (2007), PayPal co-founder Peter Thiel (2007), eBay co-founder Pierre Omidyar (1999), Facebook founder and CEO Mark Zuckerberg (2009), Facebook COO Sheryl Sandberg (2007).

Great Britain, Canada, New Zealand

Professor Devi Sridhar (a leading ‚Äòzero covid‚Äô proponent, selected in 2020/21), former British Prime Ministers Tony Blair and Gordon Brown (both selected in 1993), BBC World Service journalist Dawood Azami, Mark Leonard (founding director of the George Soros funded European Council on Foreign Relations), Lynn Forester de Rothschild (co-owner of The Economist), Nathaniel Rothschild (son of Lord Rothschild), historian Niall Ferguson (selected in 2005), William Hague (Foreign Secretary, 2010-2014), Charles Allen (CEO of ITV, 2004-2007; Chairman of EMI, 2008-2010).
New Zealand Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern (since 2017, selected in 2014), Canadian Deputy Prime Minister Chrystia Freeland (selected in 2001; former managing director of Reuters). Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau is a WEF participant, but is not a confirmed Young Global Leader.

Germany

Chancellor Angela Merkel (selected in 1993, 12 years before becoming Chancellor), current Health Minister Jens Spahn and former Health Ministers Philipp Roesler and Daniel Bahr, current co-chair of the Green Party and failed Chancellor candidate Annalena Baerbock (selected in 2020), former co-chair of the Green Party Cem √ñzdemir (selected in 2002), media mogul and Axel Springer CEO Mathias Doepfner (selected in 2001), talk show host Sandra Maischberger, late Foreign Minister and Vice Chancellor Guido Westerwelle (1997), former German President Christian Wulff (selected in 1995, 15 years before becoming President), Reto Francioni (former CEO of Deutsche Boerse), Klaus Regling (selected in 1993; CEO of the European Financial Stability Mechanism since 2012).

_source.channelabout: Welcome to the Tennessee Audit Chat. We are American Patriot owned and have joined together to Keep America First. Our mission is to unite & educate Patriots on forensic audits in Tennessee and State Election Integrity.
_source.message:
Johnson's meeting ended without mention of the ETA 2020 draft bill we had brought and it in fact it was never mentioned the rest of the day. We split up briefly after this meeting and Fanning went to see his legislators Sen Mike Bell and Rep. Dan Howell. They were both cordial, despite interrupting their lunch and seem receptive when Fanning mentioned the bill to repeal TCA 2-9-109. Time will tell.

The group reconvened in Rep. Todd Warner's office to discuss the concessions from Johnson. Warner spent much of the time on the phone.  During one of those times, Fanning, still seething at the way the Johnson meeting had gone, said something about it in Warner's presence and was quickly admonished by Harms and Allison.

Lesson 5: Never reveal disharmony to outside parties, even allies. No matter the provocation or how crappy you feel, you just look like a bickering fool.

The tactical discussion with Warner concerned usage of a "caption" bill to create the vehicle(s) to provide for the "Public Audit" option and the paper ballot option.

Following the meeting with Warner, Harms typed up the proposed language for the caption bills and the group was joined by Gregg Koepke. After a little lunch we then went to see Rep. Tim Rudd, Chairman of the House Subcommittee on Elections and Campaign Finance.  I mention the committee because in the course of a cordial wide ranging discussion he mentioned that he has not received more than a dozen calls about the state of our elections. 

Lesson 6: Come on people, we have to stay in constant contact with these folks or they won't take us seriously.

He also mentioned that he has been cut out of any discussion of election audits and that the new bill would be solely the work of the (if my frail memory serves) Speaker of the House, the Senate Majority Leader, the Secretary of State and the Governor. He also said that he would not be in favor of a purely paper election system, however the paper + public audit system might have merit. All of these folks are going to be a hard sell on the serialized ballots with unique identifiers for public display.

There was another public meeting underway at 3 pm, but I opted to take the 2-1/2 hour drive back to Meigs county, so I don't know what transpired there or what will be the final disposition of the 2 caption bills. 

Thanks again to Kathy Harms and Eric Allison. Without them, we would have not seen any movement this session. The legislators are going to try to adjourn early to campaign, so this is all we are likely to get. Now the strategy is clear. Work on your county election commissions and other local officials. Get them to make the move to paper ballots and the public audit.

Keep up the fight.

In liberty,
Alan Fanning

_source.channelabout: Welcome to the Tennessee Audit Chat. We are American Patriot owned and have joined together to Keep America First. Our mission is to unite & educate Patriots on forensic audits in Tennessee and State Election Integrity.
_source.message:
I sent the following to a few activists on 2/15:
Friends,

Yesterday along with two others, I spent most of the day visiting with legislators in Nashville. This is what transpired from my perspective. Others may differ in their impressions, so "mileage may vary".

The group: Kathy Harms, Eric Allison and Alan Fanning. We met in the cafeteria of the State Office Building at around 10:45. Fanning had never met either of the others and had never spoken to Allison.  Spent the bulk of the time discussing one sentence of a proposed bill written by Fanning.

Lesson 1: If at all possible, do not engage the authorities (elected or appointed officials) without a clear understanding of the group objectives and intentions of the participants.

The first meeting with Senator Jack Johnson  started about  11:30 in his office. He was surprised to see more than Harms, however having met Allison previously, he seemed to accept his presence readily. Fanning however was a complete unknown. From the beginning Johnson attempted to exclude Fanning from the conversation. His body language was clearly of one attempting to ignore another.

Lesson 2: If attempting to gain what the authority considers a favor or to engage in an area they have little interest, the group should present a uniform professional image. Particularly in the case of the Majority Leader of the Senate, who is deluged with lobbyists, along with not being a constituent, Fanning's Trump hat and checked shirt contrasted sharply with the other's business attire and signified a person of little importance.

Harms and to a lesser extent Allison had both talked to Johnson previously about bringing secure, paper ballots to Tennessee and audits, so the first part of the discussion revolved around Johnson's proposed bill for risk limiting audits and whether they could introduce fraud counter measures for the ballot.  At this point Johnson made the announcement that we had been forewarned about: there will be no changes made that effect the 2022 elections.(paraphrase). Fanning asked "Why" and as Johnson was turning with an annoyed look on his face Allison answered for him. "Not enough time".

Lesson 3: If one participant does not believe in the purpose of the meeting, it is incumbent upon them either to not participate, or at least not provide the authority's answers for him. The purpose of the meeting as far as Fanning knew, was to achieve some meaningful improvement for 2022 in the Tennessee election system.

About that time Fanning made some disgruntled noises and Johnson threatened to have Fanning leave. This was also about the time Johnson announced that Rep. Griffey was not going to get anything passed. Harms then skillfully redirected the conversation toward voluntary actions counties might engage in and what the state could do to encourage them. Then ensued a long discussion of why posting ballot images on the internet would not pose a risk to the anonymity of the ballot. Finally Johnson did agree to add a provision to a bill this session that would allow counties to scan and upload anonymous ballot images.

Lesson 4: Never give up. Harms was dogged in her pursuit of any opening and it paid off in providing permission for a county to employ a "Public Audit" of their ballots.

As the meeting was winding down, Fanning directly address the plight of small counties that have obsolete voting systems, that would like to go back to hand-counted paper ballots, but are prevented by TCA 2-9-109, which requires them to have and use voting machines.  Surprisingly Johnson conceded that the legislature should not compel the counties to use voting machines that they do not want and he would support action to give them the option of hand counted paper ballots.

Lesson 5: See lesson 4
